us defense department reconsider reduction of us forces in europe
the u.s. department of defense is reconsidering plans to cut the number of u.s. troops in europe by about half in 2002 due to changes in the iraq war and the world situation , a u.s. defense department official said today .
us media quoted an official of the defense department as saying that since the iraq war is still going on and us relations with russia and iran are worsening , the defense ministry leadership has raised doubts on the possibility of reducing troops stationed in europe .
in 2002 , then us defense secretary rumsfeld announced that the united states would reduce the number of its troops stationed in europe from 113,000 to 710,000 by 2012 in order to build a " small but streamlined " new army .
at present , the total us military strength in europe has dropped to 100,000 .
however , in june this year , krakow , commander of the us european command , submitted a report to the current us defense secretary gates , raising questions on the aforesaid reduction plan .
the report says that while the us troops stationed in europe are decreasing , many of them are being transferred to iraq and afghanistan in turns to fight , causing a shortage of us military personnel stationed in europe and rendering it unable to carry out normal cooperation with its european allies .
the report recommends a halt to the reduction of us forces in europe .
relevant us experts believe that the above phenomena show that the long delay in the iraq war has disrupted the original adjustment plan of the us military .
